[~sjones], to be specific I think this is the part of code that deals with name lookups for bucket names. 

{code}
else if ( nameString.startsWith("objectstorage.") || nameString.matches(".*\\.objectstorage\\..*") || nameString.startsWith("walrus.") || nameString.matches(".*\\.walrus\\..*")) {
			//map walrus to objectstorage for legacy support
            SetResponse resp = new SetResponse(SetResponse.SUCCESSFUL);
			try {
				List<InetAddress> osgIps = ObjectStorageAddresses.getObjectStorageAddress();
				for (InetAddress osgIp : osgIps) {
					resp.addRRset(new RRset(new ARecord(name, 1, 20/* ttl */, osgIp)));
				}
			} catch (EucalyptusCloudException e) {
				LOG.error(e);
				return super.findRecords(name, type);
			}
			return resp;
{code}

We should in case of --bind-addr ensure that the IP returned is not {code}ObjectStorageAddresses.getObjectStorageAddress();{code} but it is the public facing IP so that client can access the buckets from outside the cloud if required. 

Hope the above makes sense. Just wanted to make sure this would also be covered in the work done for this ticket. If this needs a separate issue let me know and I am happy to raise a new EUCA ticket for this.

Cheers!
Deependra

So. To review:

h3. Assertions, Assumptions, and Preconditions
# *Only when* a {{Host}} in the {{system}} has *additional* interfaces beyond the {{bootstrap}} interface can the problem occur.  This means the problem is *not general* and specific to a deployment topology.
# A *precondition* to the problem is the {{bootstrap}} interface's network being unreachable from the *additional* interface networks *and* expecting users to make requests that originate from those networks.  This means the problem is in how the {{system}} answers the question about the address to use when contacting a {{service}}.
# The question of a {{service}}'s address requires that the {{Host}} serving the request has successfully joined the {{group}} and completed {{bootstrap}}.  This is the _first_ time it is _OK_ to service requests (either WS or DNS, or user or internal).
# Any external attempts to lookup {{service}} addresses before {{bootstrap}} completes are illegitimate -- we, _by design_, don't care if they fail.  This is reflected in the {{Host}} information of the {{group}} meaning that not only does the {{Host}} know it has finished bootstrap, but so does the {{system}} now acknowledge it and any hosted {{services}}.
# The {{EmpyreanService}} on the {{Coordinator}} {{Host}} is the _de facto_ owner of all services in the {{system}} and is the first mover.  This means that the time interval of concern is constrained to when the {{Db}} exists and the {{system}} has a functioning {{EmpyreanService}} and that creates/handles the other {{services}}.  This means that the {{InetAddress}} information for all {{Host}}s is available for all their interfaces through the {{group}}.
# All {{services}} which are accessible to users are either:  the {{EmpyreanService}} itself _or_ defined by a {{ServiceConfiguration}} in the database.  This means that the {{service}} addresses in question are secondary/dependent upon getting the {{system}} up and running.

h3. All Cases of Service Addressing
 {{system}} needs to answer the user's inquiry "how is {{service}} addresded!?!1?" in four cases:
# The {{Dns}} service is responding to an {{A}} record request in {{TopologyDnsResolver}} or any of the {{RegisterableeComponentIds}}.
# The {{HttpService}} (in the {{X509Download}} servlet) is populating the URLs of services while generating a credentials # The {{EmpyreanService}} is responding to the {{DescribeServices}} operation.  This request can originate with either another {{service}} or a {{user}}.  It happens by way of mapping a {{ServiceConfiguration}} to a {{ServiceId}} in {{ServiceConfigurations.ServiceConfigurationToServiceId()}}.
# The {{EmpyreanService}} needs to contact the {{service}}.  This is at ServiceTransitions.sendEmpyreanRequest(ServiceTransitions.java:326).

We can safely disregard looking at Case #4 here because that would assume a change in semantics that violates pretty much every assumption that is a precondition of the system have bootstrapped enumerated above.

For the cases #1, #2, and #3 the bug calls for:
# Identifying when the problem is triggered.
# Determining the correct response value.

h3. Determing when the Problem is triggered
To be clear, the problem is triggered when: A user request comes over a network which is not routable to the {{bootstrap}} network.  In all cases #1, #2, and #3, there exists a sufficient condition that indicates an alternative {{service}} address must be used.  For example, the {{Dns}} and {{EmpyreanService}} are recieving the request from the user from the network in question.  This implies the following test determines when the alternative response is needed:
{code}
/**
 * Going to lookup and respond about some random service the user wants
 */
InetAddress responseAddress = ServiceConfigurations.lookupByName( "exemplary service" ).getInetAddress();

/**
 * This is the interface used by the system
 */
NetworkInterface bootstrapInterface = NetworkInterface.getByInetAddress( Hosts.localHost().getBindAddress() );

/**
 * usersLocalBindAddress is the local bind address for the requestor
 * the address is necessarily one assigned to a local network interface
 */
InetAddress usersLocalBindAddress = ( ( InetSocketAddress ) Contexts.lookup().getChannel().getLocalAddress()).getAddress();

/**
 * This is the network interface on the same network as the user
 */
NetworkInterface usersRequestInterface = NetworkInterface.getByInetAddress( usersLocalBindAddress );

/**
 * If they are the same: we proceed as normal.
 * If they are different: we respond 
 */
if( bootstrapInterface.equals( usersRequestInterface )) {
  //Keep calm and carry on.
} else {
  //This is the case where a  different value is needed
}
{code}

In Case #1 {{TopologyDnsResolver}}, we can go further and say that the correct alternative response is to use the the network address from the usersRequestInterface.  For remote services, all of their addresses are published to the {{group}} for exactly this kind of thing.

Case #2 and #3 are the *only* two places where we publish a URL which is meant for an external party to contact the system.  All other cases are deprecated or a cancer needing to be excised. There is already the distinction between ServiceUris.internal() vs. ServiceUris.remote() therein.  The ServiceUris facade should be the only thing that ever cares about the case for URIs related to this this bug.  Any state needed to make the decision has to be availble to it, and the complete logic should be behind the facade.

h3. Summary So Far
Case #1 of {{Dns}} needs the following treatment:

* Correctly bind interfaces:  The {{Dns}} server should be binding the {{any-addr}}, or, if that fails because of port53 being bound by the piece of shit libvirtd dnsmasq server, it should explicitly bind to each of {{!NetworkInterface.isVirtual()}} interfaces (cf. {{Internets.getNetworkInterfaces()}}).

* The {{TopologyDnsResolver}} needs to become like {{SplitHorizonResolver}} where each subclass returns true from {{checkAccepts}} based on the network originating the {{source}} address.  The correct substition values for interfaces that are not the {{bootstrap}} interfaces are available from {{Hosts.lookup(hostsBootstrapAddress).getHostAddresses()}}.  I think it may even be simpler to use {{Subnets.isSystemHostAddress(sourceAddr)}} returning, in the affirmative case, the {{bootstrap}} address, while in the negative case, using the originating network interfaces address.

* Case #2 of {{EmpyreanService}}} should use the exact same test to determine the origin network as {{TopologyDnsResolver}} and compute the query result, also, in the exact same way.

